ğŸ¯ Interview-Ready Closing Line
These commands cover observation, debugging, rollout control, scaling, and recovery for Kubernetes applications in production.

Think of this as â€œwhat I type during a prod incidentâ€.

ğŸš¨ Production Incident Command Flow (Kubernetes)
ğŸŸ¢ Step 1: Check if Pod Is Running                   kubectl get pods | grep cfx-ui
ğŸ‘‰ Confirms pod state: Running, CrashLoopBackOff, Pending.
ğŸŸ¢ Step 2: Check Deployment Health                   kubectl get deploy cfx-ui
ğŸ‘‰ Checks desired vs available replicas.
ğŸŸ¢ Step 3: Describe the Pod (MOST IMPORTANT)         kubectl describe pod cfx-ui
ğŸ‘‰ Looks for:
Restart reason-->Probe failures-->Image pull errors-->OOMKilled
ğŸŸ¢ Step 4: Check Current Logs                        kubectl logs cfx-ui
ğŸ‘‰ Finds runtime errors, exceptions, startup failures.
ğŸŸ¢ Step 5: Check Previous Logs (If Restarting)       kubectl logs cfx-ui --previous
ğŸ‘‰ Critical for CrashLoopBackOff analysis.
ğŸŸ¢ Step 6: Verify Service Exists                     kubectl get svc cfx-ui
ğŸ‘‰ Ensures traffic exposure is configured.
ğŸŸ¢ Step 7: Check Endpoints (TRAFFIC DEBUG)           kubectl get endpoints cfx-ui
ğŸ‘‰ <none> means service not routing to pods.
ğŸŸ¢ Step 8: Check Recent Cluster Events               kubectl get events --sort-by=.metadata.creationTimestamp
ğŸ‘‰ Detects scheduling, probe, or node failures.
ğŸŸ¢ Step 9: Exec Into Pod (If Needed)                 kubectl exec -it cfx-ui -- /bin/sh
Inside pod:
env      curl localhost:8080/health
ğŸ‘‰ Confirms app health internally.
ğŸŸ¢ Step 10: Check Resource Usage                     kubectl top pod cfx-ui
ğŸ‘‰ Identifies CPU or memory pressure.
ğŸŸ¢ Step 11: Temporary Recovery Action                kubectl delete pod cfx-ui
ğŸ‘‰ Forces clean restart (self-healing validation).
ğŸŸ¢ Step 12: If Deployment Is Broken â€“ Rollback       kubectl rollout undo deploy/cfx-ui
ğŸ‘‰ Restores last stable release.
